Brenda 2025-11-13 05:34 p.m.
ORDER: 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 allows the State to cloak state actors in sovereign immunity willy-nilly in any case against such an employee in their individual capacity; when the State invokes this statutory scheme, a suit between two individuals is miraculously transformed into one against the State. As the Supreme Court has explained, immunity "is a high attribute of sovereignty" which "cannot be availed of by public agents when sued for their own torts." Hopkins v. Clemson, 221 US 636, 643 (1911). To grant them such immunity would be to "create a privileged class free from liability for wrongs inflicted or injuries threatened." Id. Thus, public agents "must be liable to the law, unless they are to be put above the law . . . for how can the principles of individual liberty and right be maintained if, when violated, the judicial tribunals are forbidden to visit penalties upon individual defendants . . . whenever they interpose the shield of the State." Id. The whole frame of our democracy protest against extending to any agent the State's exemption from legal process. Cf. Poindexter v. Greenhow, 114 U.S. 270, 291 (1885). The State's Motion to Intervene under 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 is DENIED. The Court finds that 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 are irreconcilable with Article X of the Mayflower Constitution; accordingly, the statutes are declared invalid, null, and void, and the State Registrar is directed to mark them 'J. Inactive'. Signed by District Judge Brenda Popplewell (Entered 11/13/2002). @robert @Chrisiful @actxrz(edited)

@Brenda For clarification purposes, which clause/section of Article X do you cite in your ruling declaring 3209.43209.7 unconstitutional?
Brenda 2025-11-14 06:58 a.m.
The Judicial Power Clause of Article X grants this Court jurisdiction over civil cases between private parties; the statutory scheme above seeks to divest this Court of its constitutional jurisdiction in any case the State decides to invoke it.
Brenda 2025-11-14 06:59 a.m.
Sovereign immunity is not properly invoked in a suit between two individuals, and, as such, I find that the statutory scheme impermissibly interferes with this Court's Article X powers.
Brenda
The Judicial Power Clause of Article X grants this Court jurisdiction over civil cases between private parties; the statutory scheme above seeks to divest this Court of its constit...
Brenda 2025-11-14 07:02 a.m.
See Ex parte Young, 209 U.S. 123, 167 (1908) ("The State cannot . . . impart to the official immunity from responsibility to the supreme authority of the United States.")(edited)
Brenda 2025-11-14 07:03 a.m.
See also In re Ayres, 123 U.S. 443, 507 (1887) ("If, therefore, an individual, acting under the assumed authority of a state, as one of its officers, and under color of its laws comes into conflict with the superior authority of [the Constitution], he is stripped of his representative character and subjected in his person to the consequences of his individual conduct. The state has no power to impart to him any immunity from responsibility to the supreme authority of the United States.")

Brenda 2025-11-17 11:22 a.m.
ORDER: I've reviewed Defendants RobertSabbatini and AlexBoneJon's demurrers; I find all the arguments to be unpersuasive. The unlawful-retaliation claim must survive review pursuant to 5 MSC 2 1701(c) which prohibits adverse action for opposing discriminatory practices -- Section 1701(c)'s prohibition confers liability regardless of whether the employee's speech was official. The equal-protection claim also survives review; although Engquist v. Oregon Dept. of Agriculture, 553 U.S. 591 (2008) held that public employment decisions are not subject to rational basis review, it did not extend that deference, as this case alleges, to unequal protection by the State perpetrated in the course of disciplinary proceedings. Thus, even if Plaintiff cannot challenge the administrative demerit itself under an equal protection theory, Engquist will not work to strip Plaintiff of his standing to challenge the State's allegedly disparate treatment against him in the course of his disciplinary proceeding. The procedural due process claim also survives review; Defendants' argument that the State's failure to provide Plaintiff the evidence against him was not unconstituional is rejected. The Supreme Court has held that the "minimum requirements" of procedural due process include, among other things, "disclosure . . . of [the] evidence against him." See Gagnon v. Scarpelli, 411 US 778, 786 (1973). For the foregoing reasons, it is ORDERED that Defendant's Motion to Dismiss is hereby DENIED. Signed by District Judge Brenda Popplewell (Entered 11/17/2002). @robert @Chrisiful @MarchelloKY(edited)

Gutierrez de Martinez v. Lamagno, 515 U.S. 417 (1995)

Upon certification by the Attorney General any civil action or proceeding shall be deemed an action against the United States and the United States shall be substituted as the party defendant.

The Board acknowledged the fatal consequences to the plaintiffs of the un-recallable substitution of the United States as the party defendant, a substitution that would cause the demise of the action. 515 U.S. at 422.

The word shall generally indicates a command that admits of no discretion on the part of the person instructed to carry out the directive. 515 U.S. at 422-23.

Osborn v. Haley, 549 U.S. 225 (2007)

The Federal Employees Liability Reform and Tort Compensation Act of 1988 accords federal employees absolute immunity from common-law tort claims arising out of acts they undertake in the course of their official duties. 549 U.S. at ___ (slip op., Jan. 22, 2007).

The Attorney Generals certification is conclusive for purposes of removal, i.e., once certification and removal are effected, exclusive competence to adjudicate the case resides in the federal court, and that court may not remand the suit to the state court. 549 U.S. at ___ (slip op., Jan. 22, 2007).

## PROPOSED ORDER
ORDER GRANTING THE MOTION TO VACATE: The Courts Order dated November 13, 2025, denied a State motion that was never filed and, on the Courts own initiative, declared 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 invalid, null, and void. That ruling addressed issues not raised by any party and resolved a constitutional question not necessary to the disposition of the matter before the Court. See Greenlaw v. United States, 554 U.S. 237, 243 (2008); United States v. Sineneng-Smith, 140 S. Ct. 1575, 1581 (2020). Courts are constrained by the limits of the judicial power and may adjudicate only actual cases and controversies. Constitutional questions may not be decided in the absence of a live dispute or where resolution of such questions is unnecessary to the disposition of the case. See U.S. Natl Bank of Or. v. Indep. Ins. Agents of Am., Inc., 508 U.S. 439, 44647 (1993); Ashwander v. Tenn. Valley Auth., 297 U.S. 288, 347 (1936) (Brandeis, J., concurring); Lyng v. Nw. Indian Cemetery Protective Assn, 485 U.S. 439, 445 (1988); Northwest Austin Mun. Util. Dist. No. One v. Holder, 557 U.S. 193, 205 (2009). The constitutionality of 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 was not placed in issue by any party, was not briefed, and was not required to resolve any matter properly before the Court. The November 13, 2025 Order therefore exceeded the Courts authority. Accordingly, IT IS HEREBY ORDERED that: (1) The Solicitor Generals Motion to Vacate is GRANTED; (2) The Courts Order dated November 13, 2025, is VACATED and rendered of no legal effect; and (3) The State Registrar is DIRECTED to remove the J. Inactive designation from 5 M.S.C. 1 3209.43209.7 and to restore those provisions to active status in the State Code. SO ORDERED. Signed by District Judge ----- (Entered 12/__/2002).
-# Submitted by the Solicitor General of the State of Mayflower; not an Order of the Court unless and until entered by the Court.(edited)
